fields.name: Human Landers for Artemis Moon Missions

fields.content:
China’s largest rocket has blasted off to space carrying the Chang’e-6 lunar probe for a nearly two-month mission to retrieve rocks and soil from the far side of the moon, in a world-first attempt.

The Long March-5 rocket lifted off at 5:27pm (09:27 GMT) on Friday from the Wenchang Space Launch Centre on the southern island province of Hainan with the more than eight-tonne probe.

The launch marks another milestone in China’s lunar and space exploration programme.

“Collecting and returning samples from the far side of the moon is an unprecedented feat,” Wu Weiren, chief designer of the country’s lunar exploration programme, told state news agency Xinhua.

Chang’e-6 is named after the Chinese mythical moon goddess.

“We know very little about the moon’s far side. If the Chang’e-6 mission can achieve its goal, it will provide scientists with the first direct evidence to understand the environment and material composition of the far side of the moon, which is of great significance,” he said.

Like its predecessor Chang’e-5, the Chang’e-6 comprises an orbiter, a lander, and an ascender, as well as a mechanism that allows it to return to Earth, according to Xinhua.

The South Pole-Aitken Basin, where Chang’e-6 is set to land, is on the dark side of the moon that remains mysterious as it perpetually faces away from Earth.

KENNEDY SPACE CENTER, Fla. — Even a successful crewed test flight of Boeing’s CST-100 Starliner vehicle could create a temporary hiccup in plans to exchange seats between commercial crew vehicles and Soyuz spacecraft going to the International Space Station.

At a May 3 briefing here, NASA and Boeing officials said they had completed a launch readiness review for Starliner’s Crew Flight Test (CFT) mission, scheduled to launch no earlier than 10:34 p.m. Eastern May 6 on a United Launch Alliance Atlas 5. Officials said they were working no issues with the spacecraft, and forecasts called for a 95% chance of acceptable launch weather.

The CFT mission is intended to be the final test flight for Starliner before NASA certifies it for use on crew rotation missions to the ISS. NASA astronauts Butch Wilmore and Suni Williams will put the spacecraft through its paces on the mission, slated to last a little more than a week.

“It’s exciting to bring in Starliner and the ULA Atlas 5,” Steve Stich, NASA commercial crew program manager, said at the briefing. “We’ve been striving for commercial crew to have two independent space transportation systems. That’s been our goal from commercial crew’s inception and we’re very close to reaching that goal.”

A successful CFT mission would allow NASA to certify the vehicle in time for an early 2025 launch of the first operational Starliner mission, designated Starliner-1. NASA has already announced three of the crew members for that flight: NASA astronauts Scott Tingle and Mike Fincke and Canadian Space Agency astronaut Joshua Kutryk.

The fourth person to fly on that mission has not yet been assigned. “The final crew assignment for Starliner-1 will be announced following review and approval by the agency and its international partners,” NASA said in November when it announced the addition of Kutryk to the crew.

Since the Crew-5 mission in the fall of 2022, one seat on commercial crew missions has been assigned to a Russian cosmonaut, part of a seat barter agreement finalized in July 2022 between NASA and Roscosmos. In exchange, a NASA astronaut gets a seat on Soyuz flights to the station, an approach NASA calls “integrated crews” that ensures there will be at least one American and one Russian on the ISS should either Soyuz or commercial crew vehicles suffer problems that ground them.

At the May 3 briefing, though, NASA officials said it was unlikely that a Russian cosmonaut would be assigned to Starliner-1. “We expect, on the Roscosmos side, they’re more likely to want to see a long-duration flight also, so we think they’ll want to start to fly with us on Starliner-2,” said Dana Weigel, NASA ISS program manager.

That would appear to disrupt the ongoing series of seat exchanges between NASA and Roscosmos. “We’re still working through that with our Roscosmos counterparts. It’s our desire to continue to do integrated crew,” she said, adding that NASA and Roscosmos don’t have an agreement yet in place for exchanging crews in the timeframe that will include Starliner-1.

Any lapse in integrated crews, she added, would be temporary. “The expectation is, even if we can’t make that swap work, we’ll go back to the integrated crew and swapping for all of the rest of the flights.”

Space Exploration Technologies Corporation, commonly referred to as SpaceX, is an American spacecraft manufacturer, launch service provider, defense contractor and satellite communications company headquartered in Hawthorne, California. The company was founded in 2002 by Elon Musk with the goal of reducing space transportation costs and ultimately developing a sustainable colony on Mars. The company currently produces and operates the Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy rockets along with the Dragon and Starship spacecraft.

SpaceX is the first private company to develop a liquid-propellant rocket that has reached orbit; to launch, orbit, and recover a spacecraft; to send a spacecraft to the International Space Station; and to send astronauts to the International Space Station. It is also the first organization of any type to achieve a vertical propulsive landing of an orbital rocket booster and the first to reuse such a booster. The company's Falcon 9 rockets have landed and flown again more than 300 times.[9] As of December 2023, SpaceX has around US$180 billion valuation.[10][11]

Chang'e 6, a robotic lunar exploration mission conducted by the China National Space Administration (CNSA), marks China's second endeavor in sample return missions. Launched on May 3, 2024, its objective is to acquire soil and rock samples from the far side of the Moon while conducting scientific experiments on its surface. Named after the Chinese Moon goddess Chang'e, the mission is anticipated to last approximately 53 days.

The Chinese Lunar Exploration Program, structured into four phases, aims for incremental technological advancements. Chang'e 6 represents the third phase, focusing on collecting lunar samples and returning them to Earth. The program's ultimate ambition includes the establishment of a robotic research station near the Moon's south pole, paving the way for crewed lunar landings in the 2030s.

Chang'e 6 follows the successful return of material by its predecessor, Chang'e 5, from the lunar near side. Unlike its predecessor, Chang'e 6 targets the southern hemisphere of the lunar far side, specifically aiming to land within the South Pole-Aitkin basin. This region's geological significance lies in the potential retrieval of lunar mantle material ejected during the basin's formation.

Equipped with a drill and scooping device, the mission's lander is tasked with collecting up to 2 kilograms of lunar far-side material, including surface soil and rocks, as well as subsurface samples. If successful, China will achieve a historic milestone as the first nation to retrieve samples from the far side of the Moon.

Chang'e 6's mission architecture includes four modules: the lander, ascender, orbiter, and returner. These modules collaborate to collect, transfer, and return lunar samples to Earth. Additionally, the mission carries scientific payloads from international partners, enhancing its research capabilities. Scheduled to land in the South Pole-Aitken basin in early June, Chang'e 6's progress signifies a significant step forward in lunar exploration and scientific discovery.

Queqiao-2, the second communication relay and radio astronomy satellite developed as part of the Chinese Lunar Exploration Program, was launched by the China National Space Administration (CNSA) on March 20, 2024. Its primary function is to support communications from the far side of the Moon and the lunar south pole. This satellite, with a planned operational duration of 8-10 years, operates in a selenocentric frozen orbit and is equipped with advanced instruments such as GENA, EUC, and LOVEX.

Inspired by the Chinese tale "The Cowherd and the Weaver Girl," Queqiao-2 aims to enhance communication capabilities for future lunar missions. The initial phase of the International Lunar Research Station (ILRS) necessitates a sophisticated communication network to support up to ten active robots on the Moon's surface. Queqiao-2, positioned in a halo orbit around the Earth-Moon L2 since 2018, was designed to supplement its predecessor and meet the growing demands of upcoming missions.

Queqiao-2's design and mission underwent revisions to optimize its functionality. Originally planned to accompany the Chang'e 7 probe, it was later decided to launch Queqiao-2 separately. This decision allowed for the construction of a larger variant of the relay satellite, facilitating its deployment ahead of the Chang'e 6 sample return mission to the Apollo crater on the far side of the Moon.

Unlike its predecessor, which operated in inherently unstable halo orbits, Queqiao-2 utilizes a frozen elliptic orbit around the Moon for increased stability. This orbit enables efficient communication with the lunar surface for extended periods, without the need for frequent orbit correction maneuvers. Equipped with advanced communication systems and scientific payloads, Queqiao-2 is poised to revolutionize lunar exploration and deepen our understanding of the Moon's environment.

IM-1 was a significant lunar mission conducted in February 2024, jointly executed by NASA's CLPS program and Intuitive Machines (IM). This mission utilized the Nova-C lunar lander, named Odysseus, marking the first successful soft landing on the Moon by a commercial lunar lander. Despite the lander tipping to an unplanned 30-degree angle upon contact with the lunar surface, all instrument payloads remained functional, and the mission was deemed successful. However, subsequent attempts to revive the lander after the lunar night proved unsuccessful, leading to the conclusion of the mission.

The Odysseus lander's "rough" soft landing represented the first soft lunar landing by an American-made spacecraft since Apollo 17 in 1972 and the first by a private company. It also marked the first time a spacecraft powered by liquid methane and liquid oxygen (methalox) successfully landed on an off-world celestial body. Odysseus carried a total of six payloads developed by NASA, as well as others from commercial and educational customers.

The IM-1 mission was preceded by the Peregrine mission by Astrobotic Technology, which launched in January 2024 but was abandoned due to a propellant leak. The selection of the landing site for IM-1, the Malapert-A crater area near the lunar south pole, was based on its relative flatness and safety, as well as its proximity to potential water ice sources for future lunar exploration.

Odysseus was equipped with six instruments developed by NASA, including a laser retroreflector array, lidar navigation device, stereo camera, low-frequency radio receiver, Lunar Node-1 beacon, and propellant level monitoring instrument. Additionally, commercial and educational payloads were also onboard, including a camera built by students at Embry–Riddle Aeronautical University and an art project by Jeff Koons.

The mission timeline included various key events, such as the commissioning burn, trajectory correction maneuvers, lunar orbit insertion, and the lunar landing itself. Despite encountering challenges, such as a last-minute software patch and unexpected landing angle, the mission achieved significant milestones, including capturing high-resolution images of the lunar surface and successfully landing on the Moon.

One notable aspect of the mission was the EagleCam, a deployable CubeSat camera system designed to photograph the lunar landing. Although it encountered complications and was not able to capture post-landing images as initially planned, it demonstrated partial success in its intended demonstration.

Surface operations of the Odysseus lander continued for several days after landing, during which it transmitted data and images back to Earth. However, the mission ultimately concluded after the lander lost power during the lunar night, and subsequent attempts to re-establish contact were unsuccessful.

Peregrine Mission One, also known as Peregrine Lunar Lander flight 01, was a lunar landing mission conducted by Astrobotic Technology, with the goal of landing the first U.S.-built lunar lander on the Moon since 1972. Launched on January 8, 2024, aboard the Vulcan Centaur VC2S rocket from Cape Canaveral SLC-41, the mission aimed to perform scientific experiments and surface operations on the Moon over a period of 10 days.

The Peregrine lander, weighing 1,283 kg, carried payloads for the NASA Commercial Lunar Payload Services (CLPS) program. However, shortly after separating from the Vulcan rocket, a propellant leak developed, preventing the lander from completing its mission. Despite efforts to rectify the issue, the spacecraft was redirected into Earth's atmosphere, where it burned up over the Pacific Ocean on January 18, 2024.

Astrobotic's agreement with United Launch Alliance (ULA) in 2017 marked the initial plans for the Peregrine mission. By May 2019, the mission had secured contracts for 14 payloads from NASA and 14 commercial payloads, including rovers and scientific instruments. However, delays in the Vulcan Centaur rocket's maiden flight pushed the launch date to January 2024.

The Peregrine lander, based on Astrobotic's previous concept lander Griffin, featured a reconfigurable aluminum alloy bus and a propulsion system capable of lunar orbit insertion and powered descent. It carried various scientific instruments, including the Linear Energy Transfer Spectrometer (LETS) and the Peregrine Ion-Trap Mass Spectrometer (PITMS), designed to analyze the lunar exosphere.

Payloads onboard the Peregrine lander included lunar rovers and instruments from multiple countries, such as the United States, Mexico, and Germany. These payloads aimed to study surface morphology, measure radiation levels, and characterize the lunar environment, among other objectives.

The mission's launch trajectory involved a series of burns to enter lunar orbit and approach the lunar surface. However, approximately seven hours after launch, a propellant leak led to the spacecraft's inability to achieve a stable orientation. Despite initial efforts to stabilize the spacecraft, it ultimately remained in Earth's orbit and was directed to burn up in the atmosphere to avoid space debris.

Despite the setback, Peregrine Mission One laid the groundwork for future CLPS missions, with the second mission, Intuitive Machines' Odysseus, successfully landing on the Moon in February 2024. Astrobotic plans to make a second landing attempt with the larger Griffin lander and VIPER rover, scheduled for November 2024.

In summary, Peregrine Mission One represented a significant milestone in lunar exploration efforts, despite encountering technical challenges that prevented its successful completion. The mission's legacy continues to shape the future of lunar exploration and the development of commercial space technologies.

Smart Lander for Investigating Moon (SLIM) is a lunar lander mission operated by the Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency (JAXA). It was initially slated for launch in 2021 but was postponed to 2023 due to delays with its rideshare mission, the X-Ray Imaging and Spectroscopy Mission (XRISM). SLIM finally launched on September 6, 2023, at 23:42 UTC, separating from XRISM on the same day.

After executing its trans-lunar orbit injection burns on October 1, 2023, SLIM entered lunar orbit on December 25, 2023, and successfully landed on the Moon on January 19, 2024, at 15:20 UTC. This achievement marked Japan as the fifth country to perform a soft landing on the Moon, after the Soviet Union, United States, China, and India. Initially, the lander faced technical difficulties with its solar panels not oriented toward the Sun, but it became operational later, surviving three lunar nights.

The primary objective of SLIM was to demonstrate precise lunar landing capabilities. During its descent, the lander utilized facial recognition technology to identify lunar craters and relied on observation data from the SELENE (Kaguya) lunar orbiter mission to determine its location. SLIM aimed for a soft landing accuracy within a range of 100 meters, a significant improvement compared to past missions.

SLIM's development began in 2005 under the name Small Lunar Landing Experiment Satellite. It was selected by JAXA in February 2015, with Mitsubishi Electric (MELCO) contracted to build the spacecraft. The mission faced funding challenges, leading to its launch being switched from a dedicated Epsilon flight to a rideshare H-IIA flight.

The mission featured two lunar rovers: Lunar Excursion Vehicle 1 (LEV-1) and Lunar Excursion Vehicle 2 (LEV-2). LEV-1, equipped with communication equipment and scientific instruments, successfully hopped across the lunar surface, while LEV-2, developed in collaboration with toy companies, employed a hopping locomotion method inspired by frogs and sea turtles.

SLIM's operations were divided into lunar days, with the lander waking up periodically after surviving the harsh lunar nights. It resumed communication on January 28, 2024, after being dormant for a week due to lighting conditions. The lander continued to operate through subsequent lunar days, sending back valuable data and images to Earth.

Despite initial setbacks, SLIM's mission demonstrated Japan's capabilities in lunar exploration and contributed to advancing the understanding of lunar surface operations. The successful landing and operational activities of SLIM pave the way for future lunar missions and exploration endeavors.

Luna 25, also known as Luna-25, was a Russian lunar lander mission launched by Roscosmos in August 2023 with the aim of landing near the lunar south pole, close to the Boguslawsky crater. The mission, initially named Luna-Glob lander, was part of the Luna-Glob lunar exploration program and sought to continue the legacy of the Soviet Luna program from the 1970s. It represented Russia's first lunar lander mission since the Soviet era and was intended to be the first lander to touch down at the lunar south pole.

The Luna 25 mission was launched on August 10, 2023, atop a Soyuz-2.1b rocket from the Vostochny Cosmodrome in Russia. It entered lunar orbit on August 16, aiming for a landing on August 21. However, the mission faced a major setback when, on August 19 at 11:57 UTC, the lander crashed onto the lunar surface following a failed orbital maneuver. The crash occurred after a maneuvering engine malfunctioned, leading to an unintended trajectory intersecting with the Moon's surface.

Historically, the Luna 24 mission, launched in 1976, was the last Soviet craft to land on the Moon before Luna 25. Plans for Luna 25 began in the late 1990s, with various design evaluations taking place by 1998. The mission faced delays and challenges throughout the 2000s, including attempts at international collaboration and pressure from other space projects. The final design of Luna 25 featured only a lander, equipped with scientific instruments for testing landing technology and conducting research on the lunar surface.

The intended landing site for Luna 25 was near the Boguslawsky crater, with backup locations identified in case of unforeseen circumstances. The mission carried a payload of 30 kg comprising eight Russian science instruments, including tools for analyzing regolith, measuring plasma, conducting infrared spectrometry, and imaging. Despite extensive planning and investment, Luna 25 faced technical difficulties leading to its failure.

The crash of Luna 25 resulted in the loss of contact with the spacecraft just 47 minutes after the start of the engine firing. Efforts to locate and re-establish contact with the lander were unsuccessful, prompting the formation of a commission to investigate the incident. The likely impact crater of Luna 25 was identified on the steep inner rim of the Pontécoulant G crater, significantly short of its intended landing point.

The failure of Luna 25 highlighted the challenges and risks associated with lunar exploration missions, particularly in the precision and reliability of spacecraft maneuvers. Despite the setback, the Luna-Glob program and Russia's ambitions for lunar exploration continue, albeit with lessons learned from the Luna 25 mission. The crash underscored the complexities of space missions and the importance of thorough testing and contingency planning in future endeavors.

Chandrayaan-3, the third mission in India's Chandrayaan programme, aimed to further lunar exploration through the deployment of a Vikram lunar lander and a Pragyan lunar rover, alongside a propulsion module facilitating the journey from Earth orbit to lunar orbit. Launched on 14 July 2023 from Satish Dhawan Space Centre, it successfully entered lunar orbit on 5 August, marking the first landing near the lunar south pole on 23 August at 69°S, a milestone for India as the fourth country to achieve such a feat. The lander and rover, however, faced operational limitations due to the onset of the lunar night, ceasing surface operations twelve days post-landing.

The mission builds upon the previous Chandrayaan-2 attempt in 2019, which encountered challenges during the lander's descent near the lunar south pole. Chandrayaan-3's landing site in this region holds scientific significance due to the presence of ice, providing valuable insights into lunar and Earth history, and potentially serving as a resource for future missions and exploration. Collaborative efforts with ESA and NASA support tracking and data transmission, enhancing global cooperation in space exploration.

Notable achievements of Chandrayaan-3 include a laser experiment conducted in collaboration with NASA's Lunar Reconnaissance Orbiter, utilizing a retroreflector onboard the Vikram lander. This experiment aimed to aid in determining the lander's location on the lunar surface, contributing to future missions' navigation and research. Additionally, the mission objectives encompassed engineering a safe landing, demonstrating rover capabilities, and conducting experiments to study lunar materials' composition.

The spacecraft comprises three main components: the propulsion module, the Vikram lander, and the Pragyan rover. The propulsion module facilitated lunar orbit insertion and later returned to Earth orbit for continued scientific observations. The Vikram lander executed a controlled descent, equipped with improved altitude control mechanisms to enhance landing precision. The Pragyan rover, designed for surface exploration, conducted various measurements to analyze lunar soil composition and surface features.

Payloads aboard the lander and rover included instruments to measure thermal conductivity, seismic activity, plasma density, and elemental composition of lunar materials. Additionally, the propulsion module housed a spectrometer for Earth observations from lunar orbit, contributing to broader scientific objectives.

Following successful lunar orbit insertion, the lander performed a series of descent maneuvers, culminating in a soft touchdown on 23 August. The rover, deployed soon after, conducted surface operations until 3 September, completing its assigned tasks before entering sleep mode due to the onset of the lunar night. A brief 'hop' experiment demonstrated mobility capabilities, showcasing potential for future sample return missions.

The propulsion module transitioned back to Earth orbit, utilizing remaining fuel for scientific observations and trajectory validation. Subsequent maneuvers raised its apogee and facilitated lunar flybys before exiting lunar orbit. Currently orbiting Earth, the module continues operations, contributing to ongoing research efforts and paving the way for future lunar missions.

Space tourism has the potential to be a game-changer for nations with thriving tourism industries. These countries, already accustomed to welcoming visitors seeking unforgettable experiences, stand to benefit immensely from the burgeoning space travel industry. With private companies like SpaceX, Blue Origin, and Virgin Galactic pushing the boundaries of space exploration, what was once a distant dream is now on the brink of becoming a reality.

At the heart of the economic impact of space tourism lies the promise of billions of dollars flowing into the economies of participating nations. As the industry matures and becomes more accessible, revenue streams will multiply, encompassing ticket sales, accommodation, dining, transportation, merchandise, and more. This influx of capital has the potential to not only stimulate job creation but also to catalyze economic growth across a spectrum of sectors.

Moreover, space tourism represents a golden opportunity for nations to diversify their tourism offerings. For countries heavily reliant on traditional attractions such as beaches, historical sites, or natural wonders, space tourism offers a novel way to attract a different demographic of travelers. By investing in infrastructure like spaceports, training facilities, and space-themed attractions, these nations can tap into an entirely new market segment and bolster their global appeal.

The development of a space tourism industry also serves as a catalyst for innovation and technological advancement. From aerospace engineering to hospitality management, the demand for skilled workers will skyrocket, creating job opportunities across a wide range of professions. Furthermore, the pursuit of space tourism drives research and development in areas such as renewable energy, sustainable infrastructure, and environmental conservation, leading to long-term benefits beyond the realm of tourism.

Participation in the space tourism industry elevates a nation's brand and visibility on the global stage. By aligning themselves with cutting-edge space exploration projects, countries can position themselves as pioneers in the new space age. This heightened visibility not only attracts tourists but also investors, businesses, and strategic partnerships, further fueling economic growth and development.

However, the realization of the full potential of space tourism hinges on several factors. Infrastructure must be developed to support spaceports and related facilities, requiring significant investment and coordination between public and private entities. Additionally, regulations must be established to ensure the safety and sustainability of space tourism operations, while also addressing ethical considerations such as space debris and environmental impact.

Despite these challenges, the outlook for space tourism is undeniably promising. As technology continues to advance and costs decrease, space travel will become increasingly accessible to the masses. Nations with the foresight to invest in this burgeoning industry stand to reap the rewards for years to come, solidifying their position as premier destinations for travelers from around the world. As the final frontier beckons, the potential for economic transformation through space tourism is limitless.

To develop a human landing system for the agency’s Artemis V mission to the Moon, NASA has selected Blue Origin of Kent, Washington. Through Artemis, NASA will explore more of the Moon than ever before, uncovering more scientific discoveries, and preparing for future astronaut missions to Mars.

To develop a human landing system for the agency’s Artemis V mission to the Moon, NASA has selected Blue Origin of Kent, Washington. Through Artemis, NASA will explore more of the Moon than ever before, uncovering more scientific discoveries, and preparing for future astronaut missions to Mars.

Blue Origin will design, develop, test, and verify its Blue Moon lander to meet NASA’s human landing system requirements for recurring astronaut expeditions to the lunar surface, including docking with Gateway, a space station where crew transfer in lunar orbit. In addition to design and development work, the contract includes one uncrewed demonstration mission to the lunar surface before a crewed demo on the Artemis V mission in 2029. The total award value of the firm-fixed price contract is $3.4 billion.

“Today we are excited to announce Blue Origin will build a human landing system as NASA’s second provider to deliver Artemis astronauts to the lunar surface,” said NASA Administrator Bill Nelson. “We are in a golden age of human spaceflight, which is made possible by NASA’s commercial and international partnerships. Together, we are making an investment in the infrastructure that will pave the way to land the first astronauts on Mars.”

For the Artemis V mission, NASA’s SLS (Space Launch System) rocket will launch four astronauts to lunar orbit aboard the Orion spacecraft. Once Orion docks with Gateway, two astronauts will transfer to Blue Origin’s human landing system for about a weeklong trip to the Moon’s South Pole region where they will conduct science and exploration activities. Artemis V is at the intersection of demonstrating NASA’s initial lunar exploration capabilities and establishing the foundational systems to support recurring complex missions in lunar orbit and on the surface as part of the agency’s Moon to Mars exploration approach.

Adding another human landing system partner to NASA’s Artemis program will increase competition, reduce costs to taxpayers, support a regular cadence of lunar landings, further invest in the lunar economy, and help NASA achieve its goals on and around the Moon in preparation for future astronaut missions to Mars.

The agency previously contracted SpaceX to demonstrate an initial human landing system for the Artemis III mission. Under that contract, the agency also directed SpaceX to evolve its design to meet the agency’s requirements for sustainable exploration and to demonstrate the lander on Artemis IV. As a result of the contract with Blue Origin to demonstrate on Artemis V a lander that meets these same sustainable lander requirements, including capabilities for increased crew size, longer mission duration, and delivery of more mass to the Moon, multiple providers will be available to compete for future opportunities to fulfill NASA’s lunar surface access needs for Artemis missions.
By supporting industry’s development of innovative human landing system concepts and designs, NASA will help increase access to space for the benefit of all.

“Having two distinct lunar lander designs, with different approaches to how they meet NASA’s mission needs, provides more robustness and ensures a regular cadence of Moon landings,” said Lisa Watson-Morgan, manager, Human Landing System Program at NASA’s Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville, Alabama. “This competitive approach drives innovation, brings down costs, and invests in commercial capabilities to grow the business opportunities that can serve other customers and foster a lunar economy.”
